            <Title>same tension as Hannah More re: capitalism</Title>
            <Text>Make an offhand comparison — Wakefield has the same tension seen in many of Hannah More’s Cheap Repository Tracts, between attempting to critique the value system implied in emerging market capitalism (in which wealth is permitted to trump longer-lasting virtues) and to harangue the wealthy for the harm their excesses inflict upon the poor, while also making use of financial schemes for people’s improvement (as in Cottage Cook). I suppose they are reconciled by the collectivist/socialist nature of the financial schemes proposed — they always consist of a few people chipping in for a shared pool of resources, from which everyone then benefits. So although they are often critiqued as ‘moneymaking schemes’, they avoid the traps of accumulation of wealth which More also critiques.</Text>
