        <Document ID="DE6598F7-A8A5-4AD5-88C1-60C50601AA4A">
            <Title>intro: lose inviolability</Title>
            <Text>What ought to be lost in distant reading, I argue, is the sense of a text’s inviolability. Many other things can be, and have been, lost in past distant readings — notably, attention to textual provenance — but these do not have to be lost. Something does have to be lost in any model of a text: as Willard McCarty astutely outlines, models are useful because they don’t perfectly replicate that which they model. But an individual human’s memory of a text, or a set of quotations copied out in a group, are models too, which lose the wholeness of the text in service of human limitations. In many ways, distant reading simply chooses what to lose, and attempts to choose astutely, in accordance with the question at hand, so that the resulting model will simplify away the less-relevant-right-now details in exchange for greater sensitivity to the details under examination. Making these choices means letting go of the idea of the text as an object separate from one’s own study of it. Whatever one is attempting to read — whether it is one text or one thousand — one must hard-code the choices one makes about how to read. This requires getting tangled up and messy with one’s object of study; it means, ironically, no longer maintaining a polite distance.
It is, of course, possible to distant-read invidual texts — I have done it often — but distant reading is at its most exciting when it uses its distance to bring more objects into view simultaneously than can easily be considered at once using other methods. Accordingly, one thing which distant reading also loses is the assumption that questions are answered with reference to three texts. But the classic “compromise position” for distant-reading — which does have its virtues — is to serve, essentially, as a slick new “finding aid” for more traditional research. Therefore, I have turned my attention to the canon of Romanticism as it is currently constructed, to seek the texts most crucial for a close-read comparison.</Text>
